  Let $X$ be a scheme. A \emph{line bundle} on $X$ is an invertible quasi-coherent $\mathcal O_X$-module: a sheaf $L$ of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is quasi-coherent and locally free of rank $1$. Equivalently: an object of the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is invertible with respect to the tensor product $- \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} -$ in the symmetric monoidal category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules.
\end{definition}

\paragraph{Status note (Phase C1).}
The Lean-side declaration referenced above currently uses a strictly weaker, global-sections approximation rather than the geometric definition stated here. Concretely, the body of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle} in \path{AlgebraicJacobian/Picard/LineBundle.lean} reads
\[
  \mathrm{LineBundle}\,X \;:=\; \mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\bigl(\Gamma(X, \top)\bigr),
\]
i.e.\ the Picard group of the commutative ring of global sections, rather than the group of invertible quasi-coherent $\mathcal O_X$-modules.
By \stacks{0AGS}, this approximation coincides with the true Picard group $\Pic(X)$ when $X$ is affine, but is in general a \emph{strict} subgroup when $X$ is non-affine. A concrete witness: for $X = \mathbb P^n_k$ with $n \geq 1$, the true Picard group is $\Pic(\mathbb P^n_k) \cong \mathbb Z$, whereas the current Lean body computes $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}(k)$, which is trivial.

The dependent chapters acknowledge this mismatch and refuse to propagate the error downstream: see the forward-compatibility note in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} and the status remark on \texttt{W.IsMonoidal} in Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}. In particular, the representability obligation (Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable}) remains a \texttt{sorry} pending the geometric definition; no chapter weakens its statement to the approximation.

The Phase~C1 refactor scheduled in \texttt{STRATEGY.md} will replace the Lean body of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle} by the geometric definition described above, i.e.\ \texttt{MonoidalCategory.Invertible} applied to \texttt{X.Modules} in the symmetric monoidal category of quasi-coherent $\mathcal O_X$-modules. After C1, the \texttt{\textbackslash leanok} markers on Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup} and Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}---which presently certify closure against the approximation-level body---will need to be re-confirmed against the refactored statements.

\begin{remark}
  Mathlib has the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules and the quasi-coherence typeclass. The combination ``invertible quasi-coherent sheaf'' is not pre-packaged; it is the content of this definition.
\end{remark}

